It is speculated that Takamimusubi was originally the [[tutelary deity]] for the [[Imperial House of Japan|Japanese imperial family]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Delmer M.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A3_6lp8IOK8C&q=Takamimusubi&pg=PA347|title=The Cambridge History of Japan|last2=Hall|first2=John Whitney|last3=Brown|first3=Delmer Myers|last4=Press|first4=Cambridge University|last5=Jansen|first5=Marius B.|last6=McCullough|first6=William H.|last7=Shively|first7=Donald H.|last8=Yamamura|first8=Kozo|last9=Duus|first9=Peter|date=1988|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-22352-2|pages=347|language=en}}</ref> According to the [[Kojiki]], Takamimusubi was a [[hitorigami]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9951|url-status=live|archive-url=|access-date=2021-10-05|website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|language=ja}}</ref>
== Mythology == According to ''[[Kojiki]]'', when the [[Japanese creation myth|heaven and earth were created]], [[Ame-no-Minakanushi]] was the first one to appear in [[Takamagahara]], Takamimusubi the second, and [[Kamimusubi]] the third.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tobe|first=Tamio|title=Yaoyorozu no kamigami Nihon no shinrei-tachi no purofīru『八百万の神々 日本の神霊たちのプロフィール』|publisher=Shinkigensha|year=1997|isbn=9784883172993|location=Japan}}</ref>
One myth tells of a bird named Nakime who was sent down to earth to check in on [[Ame-no-wakahiko|Amewakahiko]]. Amewakahiko shot the bird with his bow. The arrow pierced through the bird, but the arrow flew all the way to heaven. Takamimusubi saw the arrow and threw it back at the earth where it hit Amewakahiko while he was laying in bed, killing him.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last=Roberts|first=Jeremy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdfgjV2kw6oC&q=Ame-no-wakahiko&pg=PA6|title=Japanese Mythology A to Z|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-2802-3|language=en}}</ref>
== Family == He is the father of several gods including [[Takuhadachiji-hime]], [[Omoikane (Shinto)|Omoikane]], [[Futodama]] (some versions Takammusubi is the grandfather of Futodama)<ref>{{Cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Kami in Classic Texts : Futodama|url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=52|access-date=2020-11-07|website=eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp}}</ref> and some versions [[Ame-no-oshihomimi]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Teeuwen|first=Mark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jqfZAAAAMAAJ&q=Takamimusubi+children|title=Watarai Shintô: An Intellectual History of the Outer Shrine in Ise|date=1996|publisher=Research School CNWS|isbn=978-90-73782-79-2|pages=46|language=en}}</ref> According to ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', he is the father of [[Sukunabikona]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ponsonby-Fane|first=R. A. B.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BY23AwAAQBAJ&q=Takamimusubi-No-Kami&pg=PA181|title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines|date=2014-06-03|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-89294-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ashkenazi|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqs-y9R2AekC&q=takamimusubi&pg=PA114|title=Handbook of Japanese Mythology|date=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-467-1|language=en}}</ref>
According to ''[[Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'', he is the grandfather of [[Tamanoya]].<ref> http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=30 </ref>
In one version of the Nihon Shoki, [[Mihotsuhime]] is the daughter of Takamimusubi.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9364|url-status=live|archive-url=|access-date=2021-09-28|website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|language=ja}}</ref>
He is the grandfather of [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto]], who descended on [[Ashihara no Nakatsukuni]] first as a member of the Imperial Family and was a grandson of [[Amaterasu]], according to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''.{{Citation needed|date=August 2021}}
== Worship == [[Izumo-taisha]] is one of the shrines dedicated to Takamimusubi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Frédéric|first=Louis|title=Japan encyclopedia|publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University Press|year=2002|isbn=9780674017535|pages=413}}</ref>
Hasshinden was once a temple that enshrined him.<ref>http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=1298</ref>
